---
import Page from "../layouts/Page.astro";
import { Icon } from "astro-icon/components";
import DownloadSidebar from "../components/DownloadSidebar.astro";
---

<Page title="Download">
  <div
    class="relative isolate overflow-hidden px-6 py-12 sm:py-10 lg:overflow-visible lg:px-0"
  >
    <div
      class="mx-auto grid max-w-2xl grid-cols-1 gap-x-8 gap-y-16 lg:mx-0 lg:max-w-none lg:grid-cols-2 lg:items-start lg:gap-y-10"
    >
      <div
        class="lg:col-span-2 lg:col-start-1 lg:row-start-1 lg:mx-auto lg:grid lg:w-full lg:max-w-7xl lg:grid-cols-2 lg:gap-x-8 lg:px-8"
      >
        <div class="lg:pr-4">
          <div class="lg:max-w-lg">
            <h4
              class="mt-2 text-pretty font-semibold tracking-tight sm:text-5xl"
            >
              KaOS 2024.09 ISO
            </h4>
            <p class="mt-6 text-xl leading-8">
              KaOS makes regular ISO releases available, so any (new) user is
              not confronted with a large or complicated first update. Those who
              already have KaOS installed do not need to reinstall, a regular
              system update will always give you the latest.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div
        class="sm:mt-4 sm:p-14 lg:sticky lg:top-2 lg:col-start-2 lg:row-span-2 lg:row-start-1 lg:overflow-hidden lg:-mt-56"
      >
        <DownloadSidebar />
      </div>
      <div
        class="lg:col-span-2 lg:col-start-1 lg:row-start-2 lg:mx-auto lg:grid lg:w-full lg:max-w-7xl lg:grid-cols-2 lg:gap-x-8 lg:px-8"
      >
        <div class="lg:pr-4">
          <div class="max-w-xl text-base leading-7 lg:max-w-lg">
            <p>
              The September version ships with <strong>Plasma 6.1.2</strong> as the
              default desktop and has a size of 3.5 GiB.
            </p>
            <ul role="list" class="mt-8 space-y-8 text-sm">
              <li class="flex gap-x-3">
                <Icon
                  class="flex-none text-fuchsia-600"
                  id="icon"
                  name="tabler:apps"
                  size="24"
                />
                <span
                  ><strong class="font-semibold">KDE Applications</strong>
                  24.08.1 are included, as are Linux kernel 6.10.11 (Linux-next is
                  in the repoâ€™s, following the 6.11 series), GCC 13.1.1, Glibc 2.39,
                  Systemd 253.25, Kmod 33, Xorg-server 21.1.13, Qt 6.7.2, Mesa 24.2.3,
                  Calligra 4.0.1, LibreOffice 24.8.1, Elisa and the latest versions
                  of Falkon, Octopi, & Neochat.
                </span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-x-3">
                <Icon
                  class="flex-none text-fuchsia-600"
                  id="icon"
                  name="tabler:api-app"
                  size="24"
                />
                <span
                  ><strong class="font-semibold"
                    >For those wondering about gtk apps</strong
                  >, Firefox 130, Chrome 131, Thunderbird 128, GIMP 2.99.18,
                  Ardour 8.7.0 are among the available in their latest version.
                </span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-x-3">
                <Icon
                  class="flex-none text-fuchsia-600"
                  id="icon"
                  name="tabler:device-usb"
                  size="24"
                />
                <span
                  ><strong class="font-semibold">Media Creation.</strong> To create
                  reliable Media for booting the Live ISO, please read <a
                    href="/install/usb_flash">Create Install Media</a
                  > and follow the instructions for either using a USB flash drive
                  or DVD disc. Though UEFI booting is supported, Secure Boot is not
                  at this time. See <a
                    href="https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2016/08/microsoft-secure-boot-firmware-snafu-leaks-golden-key/"
                    target="_blank">this link</a
                  > for more on Secure Boot.
                </span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-x-3">
                <Icon
                  class="flex-none text-fuchsia-600"
                  id="icon"
                  name="tabler:certificate"
                  size="24"
                />
                <span
                  ><strong class="font-semibold">Authenticity check.</strong> It
                  is advised to check the integrity of the downloaded ISO by comparing
                  SHA256Sum and to check the authenticity through the signature of
                  the ISO.</span
                >
              </li>
              <li id="known-issues" class="flex gap-x-3 scroll-mt-24">
                <Icon
                  class="flex-none text-fuchsia-600"
                  id="icon"
                  name="tabler:bug"
                  size="24"
                />
                <span
                  ><strong class="font-semibold scroll-mt-16"
                    >Known issues.</strong
                  > Installing on RAID is currently not possible.</span
                >
              </li>
            </ul>
            <code
              class="text-xs lg:text-sm inline-flex overflow-x-auto text-left items-center space-x-4 bg-gray-800 text-white rounded-lg p-4 pl-6 mt-8"
            >
              <span class="flex gap-4">
                <span class="text-gray-500"> $ </span>
                <span class="flex-1">
                  <span> SHA256SUM KaOS 2024.09 </span>

                  <span class="text-yellow-500">
                    7713f3864dd438f8d2c8609e8d25e28fda21b3da611400fed4df3f8802641489
                  </span>
                </span>
              </span>
            </code>
            <h2 class="mt-16 text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
              Using GnuPG to verify the ISO signature
            </h2>

            <p class="mt-6">
              Besides checking the integrity of the downloaded ISO, it is
              advised to also check the authenticity through the signature of
              the ISO. For this download the KaOS Signing Key. Add this key to
              your keyring:
            </p>
            <code
              class="text-sm inline-flex text-left items-center space-x-4 bg-gray-800 text-white rounded-lg p-4 pl-6"
            >
              <span class="flex gap-4">
                <span class="shrink-0 text-gray-500"> $ </span>

                <span class="flex-1 text-sky-500">
                  <span> gpg --import </span>
                  <span class="text-teal-400">KaOS.asc </span>
                </span>
              </span>
            </code>
            <p class="mt-2">
              Next download the ISO GPG Signature to the same directory as where
              you downloaded the ISO and verify with (adjust for correct year
              and date):
            </p>
            <code
              class="text-sm inline-flex text-left items-center space-x-4 bg-gray-800 text-white rounded-lg p-4 pl-6"
            >
              <span class="flex gap-4">
                <span class="shrink-0 text-gray-500"> $ </span>
                <span class="flex-1 text-sky-500">
                  <span> gpg --verify </span>
                  <span class="text-teal-400">KaOS-2024.09-x86_64.iso.sig</span>
                </span>
              </span>
            </code>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Page>
